         <abstract>
            <p>Consider solving the Dirichlet problem $$\Delta u(P) = 0, P \in \mathbb R^2\backslash S,$$ $$u(P) = h(P),\quad P \in S,$$ $$\sup|u(P)| &lt; \infty,$$ $$P \in \Bbb{R}^2$$ with $S$ a smooth open curve in the plane. We use single-layer potentials to construct a solution $u(P)$. This leads to the solution of equations of the form $$\int_S g(Q) \log|P - Q|dS(Q) = h(P), \quad P \in S.$$ This equation is reformulated using a special change of variable, leading to a new first-kind equation with a smooth solution function. This new equation is split into a principal part, which is explicitly invertible, and a compact perturbation. Then a discrete Galerkin method that takes special advantage of the splitting of the integral equation is used to solve the equation numerically. A complete convergence analysis is given; numerical examples conclude the paper.</p>
          </abstract>
